olo.","Italian: probably a patronymic or plural form of the personal name   Emma  ."]},{"name":"Imm","meanings":["German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Im(m)o</i>, a pet form of names based on <i>Irmin-</i>, a divine or ethnic name formed with <i>irmin</i>, <i>ermen</i> ‘whole, entire’.","English (Wiltshire): from the ancient Germanic female personal name <i>Imma</i>, <i>Emma</i>, of the same origin as in 1 above. In Old English <i>Imma</i>, <i>Emma</i> was borne by both males and females. In Middle English, under Norman influence, the personal name <i>Emm(a)</i>, <i>Imm(a)</i> came to be used almost exclusively for women, being taken as a short form of <i>Ermingard</i>."]},{"name":"Demma","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Carlo, Gaetano, Marco, Mattia, Petrina, Saverio.","Italian (also <b>D'Emma</b>): metronymic, with (fused) preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘of’, from the female personal name   Emma  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sarre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, French:  see  Sare  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sarson","meanings":["English (Leicestershire):","metronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Sare</i> (modern English <i>Sarah</i>, see   Sara  ) + <i>-son</i>.","nickname from Middle English <i>Sarasin</i>, <i>Sarason</i> (Old English <i>Saracene</i>, reinforced by Old French <i>Sarrazin</i>) ‘Saracen, heathen’, perhaps given to someone who resembled a Turk or an Arab in appearance or whose behavior was thought unchristian, or to one who had been on crusade and wore a Saracen's head as a badge or heraldic device. Compare French   Sarrazin  ."]},{"name":"Sare","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Sayer  .","English: variant of   Sara  .","Croatian (<b>Šare</b>): nickname derived from <i>šar(en)</i> ‘mottled, gaily colored’, possibly applied to someone with hair of different colors. Compare   Share  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":32,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":41,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":76,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":107,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description"